<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18560514-494">
               <interp inst="t18560514-494" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18560514"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18560514-494" type="date" value="18560514"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18560514-494-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-494-18560514 t18560514-494-offence-1 t18560514-494-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>494. <persName id="def1-494-18560514" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-494-18560514" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-494-18560514" type="age" value="30"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-494-18560514" type="surname" value="CLEMENTS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-494-18560514" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM CLEMENTS</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18560514-494-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18560514-494-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18560514-494-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>, stealing 30lbs. weight of bark; the goods of <persName id="t18560514-name-218" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-218" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-218" type="surname" value="HOWARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-218" type="given" value="SAMUEL LLOYD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-218" type="occupation" value="manufacturing chemist"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18560514-494-offence-1 t18560514-name-218"></join>Samuel Lloyd Howard</persName>.—2nd <hi rend="smallCaps">COUNT</hi>, unlawfully receiving the same.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-219" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-219" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-219" type="surname" value="HOWARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-219" type="given" value="SAMUEL LLOYD"></interp>SAMUEL LLOYD HOWARD</persName>
                  </hi>. I carry on business at Deptford, as a manufacturing chemist—there are five partners in the firm—we buy a large quantity of Peruvian bark of the importers—we buy a very large pro-portion of that which comes to this country—the prisoner was in our service for about thirteen months—in consequence of certain matters that came to my knowledge, he was dismissed in Nov.—he was one of those who ground the bark, one of the millers—this (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) is the sort of stuff that it would be when ground—it is not a marketable article in this condition—this is one of the processes of making it into quinine—there being no mark or anything about this, I cannot, of course, swear to it, but as near as it is possible to swear to anything, I can, like a mechanic can swear to a tool of his own making, without being able to explain exactly why—to the best of my belief, it is my bark, I have no moral doubt about it—I cannot swear to the paper in which it is wrapped, it is similar paper to that we use.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-220" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-220" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-220" type="surname" value="EVANS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-220" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE EVANS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a miller, in the prosecutor's employ. The prisoner was in their employment some time before he left—I found a parcel of bark</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140232"></xptr>
               <p>in the water house Against the wheel—I moved it and laid it in the same place, but further up—I came on again at night, and moved it again into the mill, and let it lie till next morning—I did not say anything about it, and at breakfast time next morning, the prisoner came and said, "I think I am let into a great secret"—I said, "Oh! what is that?"—he said, "<hi rend="italic">Fred</hi> Wallidge wanted a little piece of bark for himself, and I asked him to put up a little piece for me, as I wanted a little piece for a friend, and I am afraid the foreman has found it and taken it to the counting house"—he said that it had been put in the water house for him, and when he went to look it was gone—I said that I had found it—he said, "Oh, you found it, then, that is all right, I shall tell the master"—when he said that it was a little piece, I said, "There is three or four pounds of it"—I had not then weighed it, but I did afterwards, and it weighed three pounds and a half—he said that he did not see it, he did not put it there, the other man put it there—he begged me not to say anything about it, for the sake of their wives and families; and if I did not they would never do anything of the kind any more—Wallidge was with him, and they asked me to have some beer; I said that I did not want any—I made a communication to the foreman, Mr. Mason, and he told me to let it be till he found them out, he should like to find them out himself—on a subsequent occasion I was on the grind<lb></lb>ing floor, and heard some one up stairs—I went up the ladder, and saw Clements putting a brown paper parcel into his pocket—I said, "What game now, Clements?"—he said, "I am mending my old pocket;" another witness heard him as well—he had a smock on which came down to his knees—I know Beckley, I saw him tried about three months since; I saw him on one occasion in front of the mill talking to Clements, who was at work, that was in the latter part of the summer—the bark is of the same description as my master's, and I believe it to be his—I live at No. 5, Stratford-place, and the prisoner lived nearly opposite to me, but before he was discharged he moved into West-street, I think it is called, or South-street—I only saw him twice up to the time of Beckley's apprehension, which was very soon after he left our place—after Beckley's apprehension I went with the police, but could not find him anywhere.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Will you take your oath that you saw me putting the bark into my pocket? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I am not selling my soul for the sake of revenge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-221" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-221" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-221" type="surname" value="FULLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-221" type="given" value="ALFRED"></interp>ALFRED FULLER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a labourer in the prosecutor's service. I saw the prisoner go up stairs, and saw him putting a paper parcel in his pocket—that was a month or two after we found the parcel, he remained in the service about two months after that—I have heard the conversation Evans has detailed, it is true—two or three days after the parcel was found I was talking to the prisoner, and he said, "The bark is not worth so much a pound as they have stated, by a good bit"—I said, "How can you know?"—he said, "I have a friend in London who is in the habit of buying bark," and that his friend had been an assistant in a doctor's shop—he said that we might all be as happy as the birds in the air if it was not for that b—y black-legged old b—, meaning Evans; and that we might put a few shillings into each other's pocket if it was not for him—I told him that I should not have anything to do with it, he would not put any money into my pocket that way—he said that we were not like they were at other places, but we were all against each other—I was present when the parcel was found by Evans—I was not down when the conversation between Evans and the prisoner began, but I heard the latter part—I heard the prisoner</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140233"></xptr>
               <p>swearing at Evans, and he told him to hold his noise about it and he Would stand some beer; but Evans said that he would not hare any.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-222" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-222" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-222" type="surname" value="GOUGH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-222" type="given" value="THOMAS JOHN"></interp>THOMAS JOHN GOUGH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a tailor, of No, 5, Lauderdale-buildings, Aldersgate-street. Beckley lodged with me till some short time after Nov. last, and the prisoner used to come to see him, sometimes once a week, and sometimes twice—he came invariably on Saturday evenings, and occasionally on Tuesday evenings, and he invariably carried a basket; and on one occa<lb></lb>sion I saw in it something in a brown paper, parcel—one Saturday night, about 6 o'clock in the evening, it might be three weeks prior to Beckley, being taken, the prisoner came; I opened the door, and he asked for Beckley, I told him he was not within; he seemed vexed, and said that he had come a long journey, from Stratford, and was tired—I told him if he liked to leave his banket, which seemed to be heavy, I would take care of it till Beckley came—he declined leaving it, and said that he would go over to the public house opposite, and await Beckley's return, if I would let one of my children let him know when Beckley came in, and invited me to partake of a little porter at the public house—I told my children, and then went over with him to the public house where he put a brown paper parcel on a form, and I saw a brown powder which seemed to ooze from it, as it does from these parcels produced—I did not remain two minutes with him, I had no drink—I did not see him afterwards at my house, but my children told me something—subsequent to Beckley's apprehension, I saw him at my house and opened the door to him, and I met him in Barbican after Beckley'a apprehension, and noticed that his whiskers were shaved off.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I know nothing of this person, nor yet the statement he has made.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-223" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-223" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-223" type="surname" value="OGBURN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-223" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHANLES OGBURN</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">City policeman</hi> 26). On 5th Dec, I apprehended Beckley—I searched his lodging, No. 5, Lauderdale-buildiugs, Aldersgate-street, and found some articles, but not the drugs; I found them at No, 92 1/2, Aldersgate-street, in a third floor room, a lodging which, the mother of the girl who was living with Beckley took, after Beckley wan in custody—it was a Miss Heath who he was living with—I there found the four parcels pro<lb></lb>duced—I saw Miss Heath there, that is her (<hi rend="italic">pointing to her</hi>)—I endea<lb></lb>voured to apprehend the prisoner, and went with Evans to his house, but Evans did not go in with me; I found the prisoner's wife there, but could get no tidings of him for four or five days after Beckley was taken.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-224" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-224" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-224" type="surname" value="HEATH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-224" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH HEATH</persName>
                  </hi>. I lived with Beckley, at No. 5, Lauderdale-buildings. I knew of these parcels being there, they were Beckley's property, he brought them there—I helped to remove them to the new lodging—I used to see the prisoner at No. 5, Lauderdale-buildings—I did not see him bring any parcels there of any description; his wife used to come with a basket, but not parcels—she brought me a loaf done up in paper two or three times on Saturday evenings.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-225" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-225" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-225" type="surname" value="MANNING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-225" type="given" value="JOHN WILLIAM"></interp>JOHN WILLIAM MANNING</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">police sergeant, K</hi> 5). I telegraphed to Cam<lb></lb>bridge, and from information I received, I went dpwn and communicated with the authorities at Houghton, in Huntingdonshire, on 7th March—I went in plain clothes—I had been looking out for the prisoner from the beginning of Dec.—I had seen some furniture leaving his house at dusk, on, 22nd Feb., and afterwards saw it at the railway station at Stratford, addressed, "William Leader, to be left at the railway station, Cambridge, till called for"—that was on a card nailed to each case, I wrote it down at the time, but have not got my pocket book with me: I have an independent</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185605140234"></xptr>
               <p>recollection that the name was Leader—it was in consequence of that that I communicated with the police, with instructions to watch the goods—when I went to Houghton I went to the water mill where the prisoner was at work, a flour mill, and saw the prisoner coming down stairs, round a corner of the mill inside, and Evans, who was with me, said, "That is him;" he then turned his back towards us—Evans did not say that loud enough for him to hear, and I do not think he could see Evans—as we approached him, from information I had obtained, I called out, "Simmers;" he said, "Sir;" and turned half round; I called "Simmers" again, and he turned quite round, faced me, and said, "Sir;" I said, "Oh, your name is Clements"—he paused a short time, dropped his head, and said, "It is"—I told him I was about taking him into custody on suspicion of stealing a quantity of bark and other chemicals from his late masters at Stratford—he said, "I know nothing about it, and do not care a d—for fifty b—Howards and Kents"—I said, "What made you leave Stratford?"—he said, "To look for work," and that he had been there about six weeks—I took him into custody; he said that he did not go in the name of Simmers, but I told him that he had.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Who informed you that I went by a wrong name? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> The constable; the foreman asked what Simmers had been at; I said, "That is not his name, his name is Clements," and told him what I took you for—the constable of the parish also told me that you went by the name of Simmers.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-226" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-226" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-226" type="surname" value="BREEZE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-226" type="given" value="JOHN HENRY"></interp>JOHN HENRY BREEZE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am goods clerk at the Eastern Counties Rail<lb></lb>way station at St. Ivea, which is about three miles and a half from Hough<lb></lb>ton. I only know the prisoner from seeing him at the station—he came there to receive some goods which had come down for him by railway—I cannot say how they were addressed, but he signed his name William Leader in this book in my presence—the book is in my writing, it only gives the name—I took it from the invoice—we held the goods for Leader, and delivered them to him as Leader—I did not see them; somebody else delivered them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18560514-name-227" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-227" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-227" type="surname" value="ELY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18560514-name-227" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM ELY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a publican, of Whitton, in Huntingdonshire, adjoin<lb></lb>ing Houghton. The prisoner asked my permission for his letters to be addressed to my house, and I gave him leave—four or five letters came, the first one was delivered to him by my wife in my presence—I saw two or three of them delivered to him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">to</hi>, <hi rend="smallCaps">ALFRED FULLER</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Where is the bark put after it is ground? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It is shot on the floor, and afterwards put into casks—we saw placet where bark had been taken off the hoop of the stone which keeps the dust in, that was what he had got to put into his pocket—I missed four or five good handfuls—after it is ground it runs down between the two stones, and the dust flies up and settles, that is the finest—in another room a great deal had been shot down, and we could see where it had been shot down and picked up, none was left but the dust on the floor; that was not a proper place for sifting it—we do not sift it at all.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HOWARD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What quantity do you have in a week? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> One or two tons—I cannot tell to what extent my stock has been decreased, from the immense quantity which is ground, and the quantity of dust which hangs in hundredweights about the walls of the room, and which is just as valuable as the rest.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18560514-494-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
